{"questionId":"2602747","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the following diagram, which shows the plan of part of a house.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong>diagram not to scale</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/3243ec9316c8c564e032351d69963dffb7ce242b.png\"></p>\n<p>A narrow passageway with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> width is perpendicular to a room of width <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>. There is a corner at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>. Points&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> are variable points on the base of the walls such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> lie on a straight line.</p>\n<p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> denote the length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AB</mi></math> in metres.</p>\n<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math> be the angle that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>AB</mi><mo>]</mo></math> makes with the room wall, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>α</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence, justify that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> is a minimum when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>arctan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mi>α</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> OR concave up (or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>(and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>arctan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math>, hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> is a minimum)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2602747","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ1.11di","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, justify that L is a minimum when α=arctan 2.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.7—The second derivative","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.15—Further derivatives and indefinite integration of these, partial fractions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Reciprocal trig ratios and their pythagorean identities. Inverse circular functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
